Full disclosure: @ da_667 actually inspired me. Worth showing what reporters go through too.
Lessons: Cybersecurity firms, support your researchers. If you block me, I'll cut you out. Researchers: I respect you & your work. (11/11)
The research is awesome. But now the firm won't be in my story. Just the guy. Way to go, greedy over-controlling PR. You failed. (10/x)
It's not. Although, @ da_667 is an awesome person. My story won't be out for 3 months.
Has the researcher been unavailable? No. He didn't even know I was looking for him. So, we talk. It's obvious he was being sold out. (9/x)
I find out the researcher works on a project, so I reach out to those guys instead. They put me in touch with him - right away. (8/x)
PR guy really pushes CEO. I agree to interview. But I keep pushing it off. I really want that researcher! (7/x)
Him: Talk to our CEO! Me: But your researcher did the report. Him: Well, researcher isn't available. Me: That's okay, I'll wait. (6/x)
A few hours later, an outside PR agency representing the cybersecurity company calls. "We'll connect you!" PR guy says. "Great!" I say (5/x)
So, I figure out where this researcher works, and I contact his employer. They'll connect me to him, I think. Ha. Right. (4/x)
Pro tip, infosec researchers: Don't make yourselves hard to find. It won't help when a respectful, curious reporter needs you. (3/x)
So, I come across some fantastic infosec research. I try to find the researcher, but he's really hard to track down. (2/x)
Allow me to share an interesting story about how an infosec company CEO tried to take credit for a researcher's work. (1/x)
